<m1>NO ABSENTEE BALLOTS WILL BE ALLOWED<ue4>18A<ql>
<m2><ql>
<m1><ue5><m2><ql>
<m1><styl>by <m0>By JUAN O. TAMAYO<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Staff Writer<ep>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (--) Allegations of plots to murder a presidential candidate. Alarm over possible vote fraud by a sly caudillo. The school year closed four weeks early out of fear of campaign violence.<ep>
   In some ways, a typically nasty campaign is taking place for elections next Thursday in the Dominican Republic (--) along with Cuba, Haiti and Mexico the last Latin American nations to master the art of democratic balloting.<ep>
   But if all goes well, the presidential vote could mark a sea change for 7.5 million Dominicans (--) one million living in the United States (--) and jump start an economy stalled by fears of turmoil.<ep>
   President Joaquin Balaguer, 89, will step down. For the first time in decades the rightist Balaguer and his perennial leftist foe, Juan Bosch, will be absent from the national stage. Their rivalry dates to the times of Rafael Leonidas Trujillo, who ruled with Balaguer's support (--) while Bosch fulminated from exile (--) until the dictator was assassinated in <m2><ql>
<ql>
